            <!-- Contents -->
            <noteGrp type="workDesc">
               <note type="description">Maxims, consisting of a number of short conundrums, counsels, instruction, intimations, quotations and allusions. Gerald Elmore (see ‘A Selection of texts on the theme of praise from some gnomic works by Ibn ʿArabī’ in JMIAS 23, pp. 58-85) feels that this text is closely related to K. al-Shawāhid (RG 689), but further research is needed to ascertain which came first. See Chodkiewicz, Ocean, 90–94.</note>
               <note type="structure">Structure of Work</note>
               <note type="contentsNote">Note on Contents</note>
            </noteGrp>
            <!-- Stemmatics -->
            <note type="stemmatics">OY lists 23 mss., of which four can be considered historic. The best is a holograph, Yusuf Ağa 4868 (ms. stolen, so only a digitised microfilm is now available). Ayasofia 4817 is dated 649H in Konya and was possibly read before SQ.</note>
